  "prompt": "Why does pubic and body hair stop growing after it reaches a certain length?",
  "response": "Pubic and body hair stop growing after reaching a certain length due to the hair growth cycle, which consists of three main phases: anagen (growth phase), catagen (transition phase), and telogen (resting phase). Here's how it works:\n\n1. **Anagen Phase**: This is the active growth phase where hair follicles produce new hair cells. The length of the anagen phase varies depending on the type of hair. For example, scalp hair has a long anagen phase (2\u20137 years), which is why it can grow much longer. In contrast, body and pubic hair have a much shorter anagen phase (a few weeks to months), limiting their maximum length.\n\n2. **Catagen Phase**: After the anagen phase, the hair follicle enters a brief transition phase (catagen), lasting about 2\u20133 weeks. During this phase, the hair stops growing, and the follicle shrinks.\n\n3. **Telogen Phase**: This is the resting phase, where the hair remains in the follicle but is no longer actively growing. After a few months, the hair sheds, and the follicle re-enters the anagen phase to start the cycle again.\n\nThe key difference between body/pubic hair and scalp hair is the duration of the anagen phase. Since body and pubic hair have a shorter anagen phase, they stop growing sooner and naturally reach a shorter maximum length. This is a genetically determined characteristic that varies by individual and hair type.",
